Interpublic Group of Companies, Inc.

909 Third Avenue 
New York NY 10022 United States
Phone: +1 212-___-____
Fax: +1 212-___-____
http://www.interpublic.com





155
Managers




300
IT employees




$293.9MEST.
IT Budget




The Interpublic Group of Companies, Inc. is a worldwide ad conglomerate with more than 43,000 employees. The company owns more than 800 agencies that provides advertising, public relations, and marketing communications services globally through four operating groups: The Partnership (Lowe… MoreThe Interpublic Group of Companies, Inc. is a worldwide ad conglomerate with more than 43,000 employees. The company owns more than 800 agencies that provides advertising, public relations, and marketing communications services globally through four operating groups: The Partnership (Lowe and Draft), McCann WorldGroup, FCB Group, and the Sports and Entertainment Group. Interpublic also provides advertising and marketing services through stand-alone agencies such as Deutsch and Gotham. Interpublic's ad networks serve more than 40 global accounts in 20 countries, including such brands as Nestlé and Coca-Cola. 

The IT budget is finalized in Q3.
The Interpublic Group of Companies, Inc. is a worldwide ad conglomerate with more than 43,000 employees. The company owns more than 800 agencies that provides advertising, public relations, and marketing communications services globally through four operating groups: The Partnership (Lowe… MoreThe Interpublic Group of Companies, Inc. is a worldwide ad conglomerate with more than 43,000 employees. The company owns more than 800 agencies that provides advertising, public relations, and marketing communications services globally through four operating groups: The Partnership (Lowe and Draft), McCann WorldGroup, FCB Group, and the Sports and Entertainment Group. Interpublic also provides advertising and marketing services through stand-alone agencies such as Deutsch and Gotham. Interpublic's ad networks serve more than 40 global accounts in 20 countries, including such brands as Nestlé and Coca-Cola. 

The IT budget is finalized in Q3.

The company's FCB and Hill Holliday subsidiaries are profiled separately on this database.

The IT department at Interpublic Group of Companies, Inc. is primarily run out of the headquarters in New York, NY, and is handled by a chief executive who oversees the entire department, especially the company's Global Information Services (GIS) division. This division houses staff who handle global telecommunications and run financial planning and budget analysis for various aspects of IT. The main IT department works with executives from its subsidiaries. They share common IT services such as financial and enterprise applications. This group si involved with evaluating BYOD solutions, and currently uses Airwatch as its mobile device management solution. Interpublic Group of Companies, Inc. has a number of CIOs running IT for these subsidiaries including MRM, Draftfcb, and Deutsch, a division of Lowe Worldwide. These executives are primarily responsible for IT operations at these locations but report to the GIS division as IT is mostly standardized across IPG with all hardware and software agreements going through corporate IT. 

In general, the GIS division focuses on application development and IT procurement. On the infrastructure side, a team manages a data center located in New York as well as information security and networking. This group will be increasing security spending in enterprise security management, identity and access management, mobile security/contingency, and fraud prevention (currently Ironport). Also in 2013, the company will evaluate federated identity security options. Currently, the company uses policy reviews, data storage inventory, incident response, mobile encryption, and malware software as security measures. The majority of the company's SAP staff works overseas in Europe, with a few in the US. This team is evaluating a possible cloud implementation after addressing concerns in the lagging ability to control and recover data, and assurances around where data resides physically. 
   Many of the contacts in the GIS division work closely with existing security projects. As of Q1 2013, Interpublic plans to increase security spending in enterprise security management, identity and access management, mobile security, storage security, and continuity fraud. It will evaluate the need for a federated identity security and single sign-on initiatives in the next year. Currently, Interpublic has regular policy reviews, inventory of personal employee and customer data, inventory of locations where data is stored, documented incident response process, encryption of mobile devices, malware and virus protection software on all devices in place. 

Interpublic outsources a data center as well as some IT infrastructure operations to Scott Technology Center (STC). The partnership started in 2010 with a three phase build-out of Interpublic's IT infrastructure at STC's Omaha location. The company is also involved in a major virtualization initiative encompassing servers, applications, and desktops. Additionally, the company is using Tracx as a SaaS to gather and analyze its Big Data of social media.

IT Intelligence Snippets
2013:
•1-5 pb data volume company-wide across 2 to 5 data centers, and expects an annual data growth of 1-5%. 
•Less than 10% of its servers are to be virtualized by the end of 2013. 
•Corporate IT manages 500 mobile devices, while 25000 are managed elsewhere.
•Corporate IT manages 35000 desktops, while 10000 are managed elsewhere. 
•Standardized on 1-2 product vendors with a limited set of hardware.
•Data center strategy is centered on standardizing on unified server, storage, and network stacks, and minimizing cost. 
•Long term plan for running new applications is to add servers and virtualize, but no new facilities are scheduled.





